<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-251-942  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 251 942.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  March 20 1990 pA4(W) pA4(E) 21 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Corning boosts fiber output capacity and designs tougherfiberoptic cable. (company profile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pechter, Kerry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Corning Inc, intent on staying at the forefront of the fiber-opticindustry, has increased its fiber production capacity more than 50percent.andP;  The company has also developed a new and tougher kind offiber-optic cable.andP;  Corning is lobbying in Washington, opposinglegislative impediments to increased fiber use.andP;  And Corning hasformed joint ventures, aiming to broaden product lines and gainentry to foreign markets.andP;  So far, fiber has mostly been used forlong-haul telephone service and for communications betweencomputers, but Corning sees a growing demand for fiber in the'local loop,' where fiber could replace copper wire and coaxialcable, bringing video and telephone services to homes.andP;  Because ofits carrying capacity and accuracy, fiber could mean hosts of newelectronic products and services in the coming decade, bringingconsumers hundreds of television channels and access to variousdata bases.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Corning Inc. (planning).andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsTelephone systemsGrowthStrategic PlanningTelecommunicationsCompany ProfileOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>